Part I - (prosper Loan Data)¶

by (ojiaku triumph chizaram)¶

Introduction¶

This data set contains 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan, including loan amount, borrower rate (or interest rate), current loan status, borrower income, and many others.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

This data set contains 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan, including loan amount, borrower rate (or interest rate), current loan status, borrower income, and many others

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I'm most interested in figuring out what features are best for predicting borrower's Annual Percentage Rate (Borrower APR) for the loan and affecting the employment zstatus.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I gathered data and all the required informations from 'LoanOriginalAmount', 'BorrowerAPR', 'BorrowerRate,'StatedMonthlyIncome', 'Term', 'ProsperRating (Alpha)', "ProsperScore" 'EmploymentStatus','ListingCreationDate','Occupation','AvailableBankcardCredit','CreditGrade',"DebtToIncomeRatio"

# Convert ProsperRating to an ordered type
rate_order = ['HR','E','D','C','B','A','AA']
ordered_var = pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype(ordered = True, categories = rate_order)
available_data.loc[:,'ProsperRating (Alpha)'] = available_data.loc[:,'ProsperRating (Alpha)'].astype(ordered_var, copy=True)
In [11]:
# Convert  Employment status to an ordered type
employment_order = ['Employed','Self-employed','Full-time','Part-time','Retired','Other','Not employed', 'Not available']
ordered_var = pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype(ordered = True, categories = employment_order)
available_data.loc[:,'EmploymentStatus'] = available_data.loc[:,'EmploymentStatus'].astype(ordered_var, copy=True)

# plot matrix of numeric features against categorical features.

def boxgrid(x, y, **kwargs):
    """ Quick hack for creating box plots with seaborn's PairGrid. """
    default_color = sb.color_palette()[2]
    sb.boxplot(x, y, color = default_color)
    

g = sb.PairGrid(data = available_data_samp, y_vars = ['ProsperScore','BorrowerRate'
],x_vars = ['Term', 'ProsperRating (Alpha)', 'EmploymentStatus'], height = 3, aspect = 1.5)

g.map(boxgrid);
plt.xticks(rotation=90);
g.fig.suptitle('ProsperScore and BorrowerRate Vs categorical features');
plt.show();
looking at the result gotten from the box plot, it was observerd that the distribution of different credit risks and the BorrowerRate is that there is a negative correlation between having a higher score and a lower interest rate.

plt.xlabel("Prosper Rating (Alpha)");
plt.ylabel("Borrower APR");

plt.subplot(3,1,3)
sb.violinplot(data=available_data, x='ProsperScore', y='BorrowerAPR', color=base_color);
plt.ylim((0,0.4));
plt.xlabel("Prosper Score");
plt.ylabel("Borrower APR");

in the violin plot above, there is a negative correlation between having a higher score and a lower interest rate. With ProsperScore there is still a decline, but the distribution of the BorrowerRate is more distributed and the IQR is generally larger for each rating.

Conclusions¶

Employed from EmploymentStatus has the higest percentage of all the data compared to it.

The CreditScoreRangeUpper, AvailableBankcardCredit and CreditScoreRangeUpper are all positive correlated to ProsperScore and negative correlated to BorrwerAPR

BorrowerAPR and BorrowersRating has a good relationship and correlation between them, because the almost have the same values between them. While others plots do not have so much correlation between them.
